<br>
I chose Jesus Christ as my Lord and Saviour when I was 7 years old because I knew I wanted to be a part of His eternal family.  I wanted Him to live in my heart so that I could be with Him in heaven when I died.<br>
<br>
Has that reason changed at all?<br>
<br>
That fundamental reason has never <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>changed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but my reasons continue to grow:<br>
<br>
6th grade through 12th grade:  I continued to choose Christ because His Word alone gave me the foundation I needed to know what was right and wrong, with regards to morality.  He alone gave me the strength to resist peer pressure, and the peace to stand alone.<br>
<br>
college years:  My relationship with Christ, my faith grew ever stronger when I realized how many young people battled with depression/apathy.  I continued to choose Christ because of the strong convictions I experienced when I made poor choices, and the releasing of guilt through His forgiveness.<br>
<br>
early married life:  I continued to choose Christ because He was my only sure foundation.  Getting married, beginning a new job and moving away from home brought enormous challenges to me; the Rock that is Jesus Christ was, at times, the only stable aspect to my life.  I also learned what it meant to grow in our relationship through fasting during these years.  Also, a significant miracle occured which saved my sister's life, which only increased my faith.<br>
<br>
birth of our children-present:  I chose/continue to choose Christ because, oh,....for so many reasons.  I fear Him, in that we have been given such an awesome responsibility with raising our children; I love Him because only my Father walks with me in dark times and alleviates my fears and worries; I praise Him for all the blessings and trials I have;  I am amazed at the mystery of our Heavenly Creator, science and philosophy have helped me to realize that. <br>
<br>
I choose Christ because nothing, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> else in this world makes sense...there is no peace, no comfort, no security, no freedom, no light apart from the true Light of Christ.<br>
<br>
Sorry, didn't mean to write a book.  I guess I just don't have a short answer to your questions! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><font face=Calligraph421  size=2 color=darkgreen><b>There is only one Christ, Jesus, one faith. All else is a dispute over trifles. <br>Elizabeth I </b></font>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wordwolf>WordWolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Sir WordWolf,<br>Keeper of Odd Knowledge,<br>Bachelor-at-Arms</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/18/03 1:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=60.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why did/do you choose Christ?</span><hr size=1> <br>
&quot;From the depths of despair Christ now reigns within.<br>
 No longer an outcast-redeemed from all sin.<br>
 From death unto life, from the weak to the strong,<br>
 I'm not worthy to be here-but, PRAISE GOD, I belong.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
===========================================<br>
<br>
My answer's probably more than a little different that a lot<br>
of people's, especially here.<br>
<br>
I could give the very short answer, but I'll add a little<br>
exposition, instead.<br>
<br>
In 1982, I was nearly killed by a careless driver who ran a<br>
red light while exceeding the speed limit.<br>
After surviving the incident, and reconstructing the events,<br>
I came to several conclusions.  One, statistically speaking,<br>
I should have been dead-but several &quot;coincidences&quot; lined up<br>
to prevent that.   Two, I was now very curious about the<br>
answer to what happens when you die.  I had become<br>
convinced that the answer I was raised with was NOT the<br>
correct one. (I still believe that.)  Due to the usual <br>
indoctrination that one's denomination is the most correct one<br>
in the world, I concluded that if THEY didn't have the right<br>
answer, no Christian would.  (Yes, this is obviously wrong<br>
from this side of the issue.)  So, I began seeking out the<br>
answers that I could find outside of Christianity. I found some<br>
neat-sounding ones.  They lacked supporting evidence, but<br>
they sounded like what I'd wanted to hear, so I believed them.<br>
Meanwhile, I considered myself a monotheist. I believed there<br>
was a God, and that He was the creator, but I did NOT<br>
believe Jesus was the Christ, nor did I believe the Bible was<br>
more than just a neat book. <br>
<br>
Some time after that, God sent someone to get my attention.<br>
I know had a hard decision to make, once I reviewed the<br>
evidence.<br>
I could choose to retain my nice-sounding opinion, knowing<br>
it was not true, but liking the sound of it.<br>
I could choose to believe the testimony of the Bible, <br>
accepting that I was wrong until that moment.  <br>
I knew this was an all-or-nothing decision-my entire life would<br>
be shaped by whichever I chose. <br>
You can now guess what I chose.  <br>
<br>
So, the short answer is that I have a passion for truth, and,<br>
no matter how distasteful the truth can be, I would rather<br>
have an ugly truth than a pretty lie, no matter how pretty.<br>
<br>
BTW, the person God used to reach me would NEVER be <br>
viewed as a good choice by any of you.  Heck, he's a lousy<br>
choice as I see it, too.  However, no &quot;good&quot; choice would have<br>
had the exact words needed to get my attention at the time.<br>
In fact, he had asked the assistance of a more appropriate<br>
Christian at the time.  The response he got was <br>
&quot;There's no point-he won't listen.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
God has chosen the foolish things of this world to confound<br>
the wise, and the weak things in this world to confound the<br>
strong, indeed.<br>
<br>
